          "name": "What happens after a GST scrutiny notice in Form ASMT-10 is received?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The officer issues Form GST ASMT-10 listing the discrepancies, and the taxpayer replies in Form GST ASMT-11, normally within 30 days. If the reply is accepted the officer closes the matter in Form ASMT-12; if it is not, the case moves to Section 73 or Section 74 with a show cause notice in Form DRC-01. Replies are filed online."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between GST scrutiny and a GST audit?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Scrutiny under Section 61 is a desk check of filed returns handled entirely through the ASMT forms, while a departmental audit under Section 65 examines books at the taxpayer's premises after a 15 day notice in Form ADT-01 and ends with findings in Form ADT-02. An audit must be completed within three months, extendable by a further six months."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Which records should be kept ready for a Gujarat GST assessment?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Keep GSTR-1, GSTR-3B and GSTR-9 for the year under notice, the GSTR-2B input tax credit reconciliation, purchase and sales registers, e-way bills, ledgers for the disputed heads and audited financial statements. Section 36 of the CGST Act requires these records to be retained for 72 months from the due date of the annual return for that year."
          }
